      <div type="book">
        <linkGrp type="notes"/>
        <div n="J0081771" type="letter"><head type="note" n="1" xml:id="spp-J0081771-headnote-1"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-J0081771-headnote-1-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-J0081771-headnote-1-line-group-1-line-1">'Tis not shaving day, so I shall be ready early to go before church to Mr. <hi rend="underline">St. John</hi>, and to-morrow I will answer our MD's letter.</l></lg></head><head type="note" n="2" xml:id="spp-J0081771-headnote-2"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-J0081771-headnote-2-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-J0081771-headnote-2-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head><head type="note" n="3" xml:id="spp-J0081771-headnote-3"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-J0081771-headnote-3-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-J0081771-headnote-3-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head>
      <lg n="1" type="verse-paragraph"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-J0081771-line-1"> Would you answer MD's letter,&#13;</l><l n="2" xml:id="spp-J0081771-line-2"> on <hi rend="underline">New-year</hi>'s day you'll do it better:</l><l n="3" xml:id="spp-J0081771-line-3"> For when the year with MD 'gins,</l><l n="4" xml:id="spp-J0081771-line-4"> It without MD never lins.</l><l n="5" xml:id="spp-J0081771-line-5"> (These proverbs have always old words in them; <hi rend="underline">lins</hi> is leaves off.)</l><l n="6" xml:id="spp-J0081771-line-6"> But if on New-year you write nones,</l><l n="7" xml:id="spp-J0081771-line-7"> MD then will bang your bones.──J0081771   </l></lg></div>
      </div>
